As it is of senators the poet is speaking, the reference must be to some divinity connected with that body; and as no mention of a Genius of the Senate is found, possibly the reference is to the god of the temple in which the meeting of the Senate was held, or in particular to the statue of Victory in the Curia Iulia, where, from the time of Augustus, the Senate usually met. He further supports the above view that the Genius here referred to is the said Victoria, by the Letter of Symmachus to Valentinian, in which, referring to this statue of Victory, he says ut animae nascentibus, ita populis fatales yenii distri- buuntur. cf. also Prudentius ii. 574.

Schenkl, however, says the reference is to the qenins urbis Romae, which is identical with the qenins populi Romani, as, he thinks, is clear from the comparison with the World Soul of the Stoice, lines 17, 18. This qenins is identical with the dea Roma, and with this correspond the words yenit quem venerantur, and, in line 3, Romam venerantibus.
